          "body": "The bulk of the chapter (vv. 8-32) catalogues territories already distributed by Moses before the Jordan crossing. The narrator's purpose in this catalogue is not administrative repetition but covenantal continuity. Moses appears eight times in the chapter as the source of legal authority — his distributions are not provisional or inferior to Joshua's; they are the binding act of God's appointed servant that Joshua's distributions continue and complement. The phrase 'Moses the servant of the LORD' (13:8) is Joshua's highest honorific for his predecessor, and it carries legal force: what Moses commanded as God's servant has the authority of God's own command. The Transjordanian tribes of Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh hold their land by Mosaic grant, not Joshuanic grant, and both are equally valid expressions of the one covenant. The careful enumeration of Sihon's territory (vv. 9-12, 15-21) and Og's territory (vv. 12, 29-31) ties the Transjordanian allotments to their military history — land taken from specific kings in specific battles, not from abstract conquest."
