        "excerpt": "So Moses gave an inheritance to the tribe of the sons of Reuben according to their families.",
        "body": "The tribal boundary lists begin with Reuben, the firstborn of Jacob whose birthright had been forfeited (Gen. 49:3-4; 1 Chr. 5:1) but whose tribal portion is the first named. The allotment follows the territory of Sihon king of the Amorites — from Aroer on the Arnon north to Heshbon, encompassing the plateau cities of Dibon, Bamoth-baal, Beth-baal-meon, Jahaz, and the slopes of Pisgah (vv. 16-20). The recurrence of 'all the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites who reigned in Heshbon' (v. 21, echoing v. 10) is the narrator's way of grounding the allotment in historical military precedent — this land was won from a named king in a named battle, and its distribution to Reuben is the covenant consequence of that victory.\n\nThe naming of Pisgah in verse 20 carries unmistakable pathos. It was on Pisgah that Moses stood and saw the land he would not enter (Deut. 3:27; 34:1). It was on Pisgah that Moses died (Deut. 34:5). Reuben's inheritance includes the mountain of Moses's death — the boundary point where the greatest Israelite who had ever lived gazed at Canaan from outside. The narrator does not comment on this; no commentary is needed. The reader of the Hebrew canon feels it.\n\nVerse 22 inserts the death of Balaam into the Reubenite boundary list. The syntax is casual — 'the sons of Israel also killed Balaam the son of Beor, the diviner, with the sword among the rest of their slain' — but the designation 'the diviner' is pointed. Balaam is not called a prophet, a seer, or even a false prophet. He is called *qasam* — a practitioner of divination, forbidden in Deuteronomy 18:10. The Numbers 31:8 account of his death in the Midianite campaign is being confirmed here as part of the Transjordanian settlements. Embedded in a land-deed is a reminder that the spiritual enemy of Israel who could not curse them with his mouth was eventually dealt with by the sword. Peter Davids's principle applies here even in an OT context: false teachers who corrupt the people of God do not escape the judgment of God.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishor* (plateau/plain, vv. 9, 16, 17, 21) is the Transjordanian plateau term — used repeatedly to describe the flat agricultural land east of the Dead Sea that became Reuben's territory. *Qasam* (diviner, v. 22) — forbidden practice (Deut. 18:10); the term deliberately distinguishes Balaam from Israel's legitimate prophetic tradition."
